    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3559996828" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3559996828" />
    <a title="William Leight" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26434330-william-leight"><img alt="William Leight" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3559996828?book_show_action=true">Sep 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="William Leight" class="user" itemprop="url" name="William Leight" href="/user/show/26434330-william-leight">William Leight</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3559996828" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16458080800003460088">The setup for this book is based on that of a classic English country house mystery, though in this case the country house is a planet that is off-limits to all but a tiny handful of humans to prevent criminals from extracting an extremely valuable drug from the native aliens by torturing them to death. Naturally, then, the reader immediately realizes that some of the tourists who are visiting this world are in fact criminals, but rather than allow us to try to guess which of them are the bad gu</span>
  <span id="freeText16458080800003460088" style="display:none">The setup for this book is based on that of a classic English country house mystery, though in this case the country house is a planet that is off-limits to all but a tiny handful of humans to prevent criminals from extracting an extremely valuable drug from the native aliens by torturing them to death. Naturally, then, the reader immediately realizes that some of the tourists who are visiting this world are in fact criminals, but rather than allow us to try to guess which of them are the bad guys, Tiptree tells us almost right away. This at first seems strange, but it is in fact unavoidable: unlike in a classic country house mystery, where the theft or murder can be committed in secrecy, the proposed crime here is too long in duration and too large in scope to make concealment feasible. The problem is not so much that suspense is lost, as Tiptree brings some back by making the reader wonder how the criminals will be thwarted, rather than who they are: instead, the issue arises from the fact that since we don't have to guess who the criminals are, we have one fewer reason to care about each character's subplot. These must instead stand or fall on their own, and unfortunately more of them fall than stand. This is not necessarily Tiptree's fault, as a country house mystery is not designed to allow its readers to become invested in its characters: there are too many of them, and the book covers too short of a period of time for them to develop in an interesting fashion. But the result is that the book is essentially set up to fail. This is in particularly clear relief in the extended post-thwarting coda (not a spoiler, as it's pretty clear that the bad guys are not going to win), which is spent entirely in resolving subplots that for the most part I simply didn't care that much about. In the end, Tiptree has tried to write a country house mystery without the mystery, and although her imagination can cover some of the issues with doing so, she can't quite make it work.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16458080800003460088" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


