  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1582157177" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1582157177" />
    <a title="Christian Schwoerke" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24022721-christian-schwoerke"><img alt="Christian Schwoerke" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1582157177?book_show_action=true">Mar 17, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christian Schwoerke" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christian Schwoerke" href="/user/show/24022721-christian-schwoerke">Christian Schwoerke</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1582157177" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13660969022550663102">As novel, Brightness Falls from the Air is mediocre, but as reading experience—when infusing the novel with the externality of its Sheldon/Tiptree authorship—this is a four-star experience. <br/><br/>In a life characterized by social and sexual awkwardness, Alice B. Sheldon probably found her greatest satisfaction when writing as the James Tiptree, Jr., a writer who burst onto the science fiction scene with a clarity of voice, a dark and disturbing vision, and a pronounced assurance that could only be mas</span>
  <span id="freeText13660969022550663102" style="display:none">As novel, Brightness Falls from the Air is mediocre, but as reading experience—when infusing the novel with the externality of its Sheldon/Tiptree authorship—this is a four-star experience. <br /><br />In a life characterized by social and sexual awkwardness, Alice B. Sheldon probably found her greatest satisfaction when writing as the James Tiptree, Jr., a writer who burst onto the science fiction scene with a clarity of voice, a dark and disturbing vision, and a pronounced assurance that could only be masculine. While accomplished in her own right—attractive, intelligent, athletic and poised, professionally competent and diverse—Sheldon was never comfortable in her own skin, nor in her own gender, and the frustrations of being a woman in a man’s world, and a woman who did not understand other women, made her question fundamental things: sex, gender roles, purpose, life itself. Much of her early fiction as Tiptree was the exploration of the yin and yang impulses of sex and death.<br /><br />So… why so much dwelling on the author when reading this particular novel? Because Sheldon had perpetrated the fiction of Tiptree—which included his/her public unmasking in 1977—there was always a second layer to her work, one that was informed by knowledge that this forceful, disturbing authorial presence was a woman asserting masculine prerogatives and at the same time trying to undermine masculine assumptions about the nature of things, including fiction. Sheldon published Darkness Falls from the Air in 1987, two years before she took her (and her husband’s) life. She had had from the outset of her unmasking felt a diminution as author and presence, had felt that her readers were no longer assured of her authority. With so much in her life converging to fulfill her sense of a dark entropy, it is a compelling opportunity to read Darkness as a final statement, a summing up, an effort to create even while universal forces ineluctably broke things down.<br /><br />The title of this novel is a line from Thomas Nashe’s poem “celebrating” London’s 1597 plague, a series of devotional verses that speak of temporality and religious salvation/eternity:<br /><br />Beauty is but a flower<br />Which wrinkles will devour;	<br />Brightness falls from the air;	<br />Queens have died young and fair;	<br />Dust hath closed Helen’s eye;	<br />I am sick, I must die—<br />Lord, have mercy on us!<br /><br />This particular verse aptly matches the circumstances of Cory’s accelerated death in the novel’s final pages. This former robust and athletic guardian of Damiem has been prematurely made senescent, and she is reflecting on all that her life has encompassed—notably the misguided destruction of an entire civilization and solar system. The dead star’s last, world-enveloping eddy has been the novel’s background event, the brightness that has illumined the dark doings of poachers who attempt to re-institute a cruel harvesting of a powerful drug exuded from the glands of maimed and tortured winged beings whom Cory has been entrusted to protect.<br /><br />Cory tries to explain in a final, adrenaline-fueled speech what she has learned by growing old: “Before he died … the alien told me something that changed the whole picture. He said that in their antiquity, when they already had a high culture, an invisible entity, a space-borne something, quite likely from outside the Galaxy, somehow impinged on [their planet]. There was no doubt of its presence; its effect took the form of a great and growing beauty in all things; in [the alien’s] words, ‘Beauty such as no one had ever seen or imagined … even the trees, weeds, rocks … like those here.’ And after generations of exposure to this beauty, the people of [the planet] began to weaken and die. They had no doubt as to the cause.”<br /><br />Cory goes on: “The form of this disease seems to have been a terrible loss of the ability to hope, a boundless despair—coupled with what [the alien] called ‘an unquenchable, unnamable desire,’ a yearning… As if the entity had fed on the souls of the beholders. … ‘When it had fed full, it compelled us to build’ … It was a gigantic work of art, with all the culture and history of their race, and powered so that it might, I quote, ‘go forth through the Galaxy, feeding and reproducing.’ … [The alien] seemed to reverence it and hate it bitterly…”<br /><br />The ambivalence of emotion and purpose that Cory expresses merges with her character’s role in the novel, as author of all the events that transpire, good and bad. She and Tiptree are talking about things beyond the space opera that is the novel’s story. The muddle of reverence and hate, works of art that suck souls, of light that illumines beautifully and yet enervates—all of these are emotions that Sheldon is wrestling with in desperation to understand why it is that she is compelled to continue on writing when her instinct is to end it all, to take her life. From this perspective, the story of Darkness is simply a diversion, a means to slow entropy, to prolong her own life with imaginative ruminations about the seeming contradiction of being.<br /><br />Interesting in this regard is how Sheldon/Tiptree paralyzes Cory at the height of the action, as the star eddy washes over the planet and the poachers are doing their worst to the Dameii hidden within the hostel and to the tourists who are laid out, comatose on the hostel’s deck. Though author of the difficulties all about her, Cory has been made impotent to resolve them (in which condition her male lover Kip also finds himself). It is her friend and fellow guardian Bram, the xenopathologist, who takes charge and employs the aid of the tourists, to put a stop to the drama on the stage of the hostel’s deck. <br /><br />Cory’s paralysis—her inability to act and to alter circumstances—highlights the emergence of Bram as the authority—the Tiptree factor—who can alter the story to the satisfaction of tourists (readers) and all concerned, even if Cory is at the end sacrificed to senescence. Once one begins to untangle the connections between author Sheldon/Tiptree and the characters in Darkness, the more suggestive the process becomes. This is not the way everyone will wish to read the book, and, in fact, without this extra-textual knowledge of Sheldon/Tiptree, it may seem only that the book is oddly shaped, that the ramblings of senescent Cory seem to be privileged in a way that makes no real sense to a literal-minded reader. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13660969022550663102" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

