<span id="freeTextContainer1170344171022716253">This one of of my Dad&apos;s favorite books, and because of that I probably rate it a half star higher than I&apos;d like (why no half star ratings, Goodreads?) Hmm! Anyway, the strongsuit of this book are its characters. There&apos;s over a dozen major players and from time to time you might get lost trying to keep track of them all. Like Pokemons. But they&apos;re also so well developed that they do feel distinct, and I think that&apos;s where the book hurts itself a little bit. The plot suffers maybe just a tiny bit </span>
  <span id="freeText1170344171022716253" style="display:none">This one of of my Dad's favorite books, and because of that I probably rate it a half star higher than I'd like (why no half star ratings, Goodreads?) Hmm! Anyway, the strongsuit of this book are its characters. There's over a dozen major players and from time to time you might get lost trying to keep track of them all. Like Pokemons. But they're also so well developed that they do feel distinct, and I think that's where the book hurts itself a little bit. The plot suffers maybe just a tiny bit because it's told from multiple viewpoints which I usually adore. As I've gotten older I've had a third and fourth read of the book, and I think it's really a tragedy which startlingly puts human nature and the darkness inside of us on an ugly but beautifully crafted display.</span>
